<subSubSection id="3DB73CB4279BE709B5EA58CA13ED2A1C" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="CC9C2B6C598277AC6EEF48E4FB0F513B" pageNumber="13">Diagnosis. Distinguished from all other genera of Botiinae by its unique colour pattern: three broad black bars (one through eye, two on body) on a bright orange-red background. Distinguished from other genera within the subfamily Botiinae by the following combination of characters: Mental lobe developed in a barbel. Fronto-parietal fontanelle large, elliptical. Anterior chamber of gas bladder partly covered by bony capsule; posterior chamber large. Top of supraethmoid very broad. Optic foramen rather small. Suborbital spine not strongly arched, bifid. Head naked (based on Taki, 1972: 76).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FDE70327F6225A400C1FB6F2BFF61AE5" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="22F02E056E9A95679E5C39A7F1EB927C" pageNumber="13">
Etymology. From the Greek khroma (colour) and 
<taxonomicName id="79651CE6EE23013BB6AE1A497FFB0773" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:09226C1A-9A89-4F09-98CC-848F7DBB6275" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cobitidae" genus="Botia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Botia Gray 1831:8" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="13" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Botia</taxonomicName>
, allusion to the bright coloration. Gender feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
